# How I Think About Roadmap and Priorities

Roadmap decisions are resource decisions. Every yes is a no to something else. I take that seriously.

## My framework

**Start with outcomes, not features.** What does success look like in 6 months? In a year? Work backward from that. Features are hypotheses about how to get there — treat them like hypotheses.

**Financial and business model decisions drive workforce decisions — not the reverse.** Before committing headcount or scope to anything, I want to understand the unit economics. What does this cost to build and maintain? What does it return? That's the conversation that should happen before the roadmap is set.

**Ruthless prioritization.** A roadmap with 40 priorities has zero priorities. I push hard for small, committed lists. Three things we will definitely ship are worth more than twelve things we might get to.

**Involve the team.** Engineers who understand why something matters build it better. I share context freely — business goals, user problems, constraints. I expect the team to engage with that context, not just execute against a ticket.

## On saying no

I say no a lot. To stakeholders, to leadership, to good ideas that aren't the right ideas right now. No is a complete strategy when it protects the team's ability to do their best work on the things that matter most.

I'll always explain why. And I'll always be open to being convinced — but convince me with evidence, not enthusiasm.

## On estimates and deadlines

I don't believe in fake precision. If I ask how long something takes and you give me a number you're not confident in, tell me that. I'd rather have a range with honest uncertainty than a date that quietly becomes a miss.

Deadlines I commit to externally, I protect internally. That means hard conversations about scope, not silent death marches.
